Here's a comprehensive breakdown of how to build your Method-Aware Search Engine for Computer Science Research Papers, along with enhancements drawn from your notes and the assignment brief.

What you're building
A search engine that doesn't just keyword-match — it understands the importance of terms based on their linguistic role (nouns carry more meaning than prepositions), uses TF-IDF weighting, cosine similarity for ranking, and learns from user click behaviour to improve future results.

Let me lay out the full architecture and pipeline first, then walk through each stage.



Stage-by-stage breakdown
Stage 1 — Dataset acquisition
Your dataset needs to be referenced and justified (your notes flag this as critical). Use CORD-19 (from the assignment brief's Appendix B — it's a well-cited academic dataset of CS/medical papers) or arXiv CS papers from Kaggle. The CORD-19 dataset from Allen AI is ideal because it includes abstracts, author keywords, titles, and body text — all of which you'll extract metadata from.

Key fields to extract per paper: title, abstract, authors, keywords (author-specified), doi, year.

Stage 2 — ETL preprocessing pipeline
Follow the exact 12-step sequence from your notes. Here's the full implementation order:

Load only necessary columns (title, abstract, keywords)
Analyse the raw data first — plot distributions, missing values, class balance — before cleaning
Drop nulls, remove duplicates
Lowercase everything
Tokenise (use nltk.word_tokenize)
Remove stop words (nltk.corpus.stopwords)
Remove punctuation
Remove numbers
Porter stemmer (nltk.stem.PorterStemmer) on each token
Join keyword columns with abstract for a combined text field
Convert to vector representation
Stage 3 — POS tagging and method-aware weighting
This is the core novelty of your project. Use nltk.pos_tag or spaCy on the original (un-stemmed) text before stemming, then carry the POS labels forward. Assign multipliers:

POS category	Multiplier	Rationale
Nouns (NN, NNS, NNP)	2.0	Domain concepts: "transformer", "gradient"
Hyphenated compounds	1.8	Specialist terms: "self-attention"
Verbs (VB, VBD)	1.2	Methods: "classifies", "evaluates"
Adjectives (JJ)	1.0	Qualifiers
Everything else	0.5	Articles, prepositions, etc.
Author-specified keywords get an additional boost (multiply by 1.5) since the author chose them deliberately.

Stage 4 — TF-IDF vector construction
Your weight formula becomes:

weight(t, d) = TF(t,d) × IDF(t) × POS_multiplier(t) × keyword_boost(t)

Where:

TF(t,d) = count of term t in doc d / total terms in d
IDF(t) = log₁₀(N / df(t)) where N = total docs, df(t) = docs containing t
Build this as a sparse matrix. sklearn.feature_extraction.text.TfidfVectorizer gives you a baseline — but you'll need to customise the weights to inject POS multipliers on top.
Use sklearn for the initial TF-IDF, then multiply the resulting sparse matrix column-wise by your POS weight vector.

Stage 5 — Index storage
Store the TF-IDF matrix and the inverted index (term → list of doc IDs + weights) in a database. Your notes mention PostgreSQL with vector support (pgvector extension) — this directly supports cosine similarity queries with <=> operator, which is exactly what you need. Alternatively, keep it simpler with SQLite and compute cosine similarity in Python at query time.

Stage C — Cosine similarity at query time
Apply the same preprocessing pipeline to the user's query
Apply the same POS weighting to query terms
Build a query vector in the same vector space as your documents
Compute cosine similarity: cos(θ) = (q · d) / (|q| × |d|)
Rank documents by descending score
Discuss both cosine similarity and Euclidean distance in your report and justify which you chose (cosine is preferred because it's magnitude-invariant — a long paper and a short paper can still rank equally if they discuss the same topics).

Stage D — Click-through re-ranking (your focal point enhancement)
From your notes: "if user searches A and doc 1 and 2 show up, and user clicks doc 2, another user searching the same term will see doc 2 first."

Store click events in a table: (query_terms, doc_id, click_count). At retrieval time, blend the cosine score with a click-popularity score:

final_score = α × cosine_score + (1 − α) × click_score

Where α ≈ 0.7 keeps retrieval quality dominant but surfaces popular results. This is a simplified version of what Google's PageRank + CTR system does — mention this in your related work.

