Step 1 — Combine your text fields
Before any cleaning, merge title, abstract, and any keywords into one field. Title words are more important so you repeat them (a simple way to boost their weight before POS tagging):

python
def combine_fields(row):
    # Title repeated twice to give it natural weight boost
    title = str(row['title']).strip()
    abstract = str(row['abstract']).strip()
    return f"{title} {title} {abstract}"

df_cs['combined_text'] = df_cs.apply(combine_fields, axis=1)
Step 2 — POS tagging (do this BEFORE cleaning)
This is critical — you must POS tag the original text before stemming destroys the word forms. NLTK's tagger needs real words like "classifies" and "neural", not stems like "classifi" and "neural":

python
def get_pos_weights(text):
    """Returns dict of {token: pos_multiplier} for original text"""
    tokens = word_tokenize(text.lower())
    tagged = nltk.pos_tag(tokens)
    
    weights = {}
    for word, tag in tagged:
        if tag.startswith('NN'):      # Nouns
            weights[word] = 2.0
        elif tag.startswith('VB'):    # Verbs
            weights[word] = 1.2
        elif tag.startswith('JJ'):    # Adjectives
            weights[word] = 1.0
        else:
            weights[word] = 0.5
    return weights

# Store POS weights alongside the text
