Answer to question 3 — Relevance vs Blended
Relevance (cosine only) ranks purely by how mathematically similar the query vector is to each document vector. It has no memory — every search starts fresh. A paper that perfectly matches your query terms will always rank first regardless of whether anyone has ever found it useful.

Blended combines cosine similarity with click history: 0.7 × cosine + 0.3 × click_score. This means a paper that ranks 3rd by pure relevance but has been clicked many times for similar queries will be promoted upward. Over time it learns which results users actually find valuable, not just which ones match the words. The tradeoff is that brand new papers with no clicks can be buried even if they're highly relevant.

For your viva, the one-line summary is: relevance is stateless and mathematical; blended is stateful and learns from behaviour.

